trans-unit.source: Compare to tf.GradientTape which computes vector-Jacobian products ("VJP"s) using reverse-mode autodiff (backprop). Reverse mode is more attractive when computing gradients of a scalar-valued function with respect to many inputs (e.g. a neural network with many parameters and a scalar loss). Forward mode works best on functions with many outputs and few inputs. Since it does not hold on to intermediate activations, it is much more memory efficient than backprop where it is applicable.
trans-unit.target: 逆モード tf.GradientTape ）を使用してベクトルヤコビアン積（ "VJP"）を計算するtf.GradientTapeと比較してください。リバースモードは、多くの入力（たとえば、多くのパラメーターとスカラー損失を持つニューラルネットワーク）に関するスカラー値関数の勾配を計算する場合により魅力的です。転送モードは、出力が多く入力が少ない関数で最適に機能します。中間のアクティベーションを保持しないため、適用可能なバックプロップよりもはるかにメモリ効率が高くなります。

trans-unit.source: Computes a 2-D atrous convolution, also known as convolution with holes or dilated convolution, given 4-D value and filters tensors. If the rate parameter is equal to one, it performs regular 2-D convolution. If the rate parameter is greater than one, it performs convolution with holes, sampling the input values every rate pixels in the height and width dimensions. This is equivalent to convolving the input with a set of upsampled filters, produced by inserting rate - 1 zeros between two consecutive values of the filters along the height and width dimensions, hence the name atrous convolution or convolution with holes (the French word trous means holes in English).
